t Lewis shows how they are part of a continuous intellectual tradition that stretches from the early Protestant Reformation into modern times. Through close readings of architectural plans and archival documents, many previously unpublished, he shows the network of connections between these seemingly disparate Utopian settlements-including even such well-known town plans as those of New Haven and Philadelphia.The most remarkable aspect of the city of refuge is the inventive way it fused its eclectic sources, ranging from the encampments of the ancient Israelites as described in the Bible to the detailed social program of Thomas More's Utopia to modern thought about education, science, and technology. Delving into the historical evolution and antecedents of Utopian towns and cities, City of Refuge alters notions of what a Utopian community can and should be.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningxReligious aspects. 0aCity planningxSocial aspects. 0aCollective settlements. 0aUtopias. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh  aBible.  aBlack Forest.  aCount Nicholas Zinzendorf.  aDuke of Wrttemberg.  aEconomy.  aFreudenstadt.  aFriedrich I.  aGermanЁmerican architecture.  aHarmonists.  aHeinrich Schickhardt.  aHerrnhaag.  aIndustrial Revolution.  aJohann Georg Rapp.  aMoravian Church.  aNew Harmony.  aNew Jerusalem.  aPennsylvania.  aProtestants.  aRobert Owen.  aThomas More.  aUnity of the Brethren.  aUtopia.  aUtopian community.  aUtopian town planning.  aWestern world.  acity of joy.  acity of refuge.  acollective ownership.  acommunal dormitory.  aideal society.  aindustrial capitalism.  amodel city.  amodernity.  aphysical isolation.  arefugee settlement.  areligions refugees.  areligious expression.  areligious re